[1mDESCRIPTION[0m[m
       ngrep strives to provide most of GNU grep's common features, applying them to the network layer.  ngrep is a pcap-aware tool that[m
       will  allow  you to specify extended regular expressions to match against data payloads of packets.  It currently recognizes TCP,[m
       UDP and ICMP across Ethernet, PPP, SLIP, FDDI and null interfaces, and understands bpf filter logic in the same fashion  as  more[m
       common packet sniffing tools, such as [1mtcpdump[0m(8) and [1msnoop[0m(1).[m
[m
[1mOPTIONS[0m[m
       -h     Display help/usage information.[m
[m
       -N     Show sub-protocol number along with single-character identifier (useful when observing raw or unknown protocols).[m
[m
       -X     Treat the match expression as a hexadecimal string.  See the explanation of [4mmatch[24m [4mexpression[24m below.[m
[m
       -V     Display version information.[m
[m
       -i     Ignore case for the regex expression.[m
[m
       -w     Match the regex expression as a word.[m
[m
       -q     Be quiet; don't output any information other than packet headers and their payloads (if relevant).[m
[m
       -p     Don't put the interface into promiscuous mode.[m
[m
       -e     Show  empty  packets.   Normally  empty packets are discarded because they have no payload to search.  If specified, empty[m
              packets will be shown, regardless of the specified regex expression.[m
